`crates/ctx-verify/tests` is the black-box verification suite for the whole `ctx-verify` crate's check-orchestration and CLI-rendering behavior. Depending on this subtree buys confidence that check parsing, status precedence, regen-then-recheck logic, and both CLI output modes match documented contracts (including ADR-055) — all exercised hermetically, with no real subprocess ever spawned.

All three files share the same substitution point: `Runner`/`CommandOutcome` are faked so tests drive `ctx_verify::checks`/`cli::run` deterministically. But each file's fake has a different keying strategy tuned to what it needs to distinguish, and this is the main cross-file trap: `checks.rs` and `render.rs` key by first-arg only (coarse — can't tell `--check` from `--write`), while `checks_regen.rs` keys by exact arg list plus an ordered `VecDeque` per key (needed because pre-regen and post-regen `--check` calls share identical args but must return different outcomes). Don't try to merge these fakes; the ordering requirement is why `checks_regen.rs` is separate.

`checks_regen.rs` hardcodes argument-list constants that mirror literal script paths/flags in `checks/specs.rs` — if those diverge, the regen tests silently stop testing the real code path. `render.rs`'s JSON diagnostic shape assertions mirror cargo/clippy's `--message-format=json` and must track whatever parser consumes that format elsewhere in the crate.

Invariants spanning the suite: skip-only selections always yield `Skipped`, never `Pass` (fail-closed); `Errored` outranks `Fail`; regen recheck diagnostics replace, never merge with, pre-regen diagnostics; and no JSON-only field (`status`, `reason`, etc.) ever leaks into terse text output.